When I picked up this hobby a couple years back, never did I think I would have my work published in anything! It may not be the front cover of Wildfowl Magazine, but it’s special to me and a milestone that makes me feel accomplished! 

The Indiana NWTF director reached out to me and asked if they could use one of my turkey pictures for their ad in the Indiana Hunting and Trapping Guide. This print ends up in the hands of so many hunters each year and it will forever be a memory to me that I got to be a part of it! 

🙏🏼

Made it on the front page! 

My photo of “GPSey” or at least that’s what we’ve named her…(get it!? GPS…) anyways..

I’ve been watching and photographing this hen mallard for going on the third year now. I snapped this picture of her last winter and posted it on Instagram. It just so happens that the @franklincollegebiology center reached out to me and asked where I had seen the mallard and some more information as they have a program that bands and puts these GPS trackers to collect data. 

Turns out, this lady was one of their mallards that they had put a unit on and were tracking! Pretty neat to actually talk to the biologists of a wild bird I just happened to encounter and photograph. 

Furthermore, they submitted one of my pics of her to the local newspaper for an article about their program and it landed today on the front page of the daily journal! 

💪🏻🙏🏼🦆

First Antelope! 

Colorado tag filled this morning all thanks to my buddy @chad.thurston10! 

Didn’t have quite the luck at first light when a decent buck caught us and slipped away over the property line. 

Finally was able to put a stalk on this buck mid morning and it all came together as he got quite curious and walked towards us from 337 yards. Continued to close the gap until he got a little spooked around 200 yards. Came in to 156 yards and that was his final steps. 

I’m from the east coast and have never had an opportunity at an antelope so this year when I drew the tag I was stoked! 

A memory I’ll never forget!

You will never believe this…

Headed home to Upstate NY for a few days to hunt and spend time with family for the holidays. As always, set up some hunts with friends and we were invited to hunt a flooded corn/smartweed hole and this was our first volley of birds at first light. 

Little did we know that one of the drake mallards we harvested was banded. Marking the second band in two days. We were all pumped to say the least! 

Two years ago, I had harvested a hen mallard that was banded with band number 2247-63683. Today, as we were calling the drake band in, I realized it had the same prefix numbers as mine from two years ago. We read off the numbers and wouldn’t you know it, band number was 2247-63689! Only 6 digits off! They were banded together. 

Both banded in 2021! 

Pretty cool if you ask me! Great way to end 2023 with friends in a duck blind.
